name: Renal - CVS Haemostasis
question1: Describe the role and location of the JGA
contents:
The juxtaglomerular apparatus:

  • located between the afferent arteriole and the DCT
  • Senses :
  • drop in pressure (granular cells) or
  • drop in tubular Na+ flow (macula densa cells)


Triggering of the JGA leads to:

  • Dilatation of the afferent arteriole
  • local action (adenosine ↓?/PGE2?)
  • Renin release (granular cells)
  • Note: renin release also triggered by sympathetic (b1) stimulation



  • (1) RAAS - Renin angiotensin feedback system
  • Renin → Angiotensinogen → Angiotensin I → Angiotensin II → ATi Vasoconstriction (selectively constricts renal efferent arteriole to maintain glomerular capillary pressure and therefore filtration rate.
  • (2) Angiotensin II - also has indirect effects
  • Release of :
  • Aldosterone: ↑Volume (Na+) retention (PCT)
  • ADH: secreted in response to plasma osmolality, low pressure stretch - to add aquaporins,
  • ACTH.
  • potent vasoconstriction : renal efferents > afferents → increased GFR
  • Blockade of NA uptake 1 = potentiates SNS activity
  • Stimulates Na/H antiporters in the PCT = direct effect on renal tubules
  • Stimulates thirst via direct effect on hypothalamus + increased osmoreceptor activation
  • Negative feedback on renin secretion
  • (3) RAS also triggered by neural response.
  • Baroreceptors - via ?vagus and glossopharyngeal. to stimulated beta1, increased HR and vasoconstriction.


→ ↓ ↑ ←
contents2:
Other effects of Angiotensin II


  • Angiotensin II
  • Splanchnic vasoconstriction (more sensitive than systemic vessels)
  • Mesangial cell contraction, e.g. in response to angiotensin II, decreases the filtration coefficient


  • Angiotensin II:
  • Octapeptide
  • Has a half life of a few minutes
  • Two types of angiotensin II receptor:
  • AT1 = greater affinity, G-protein coupled
  • AT2 (may possess cardioprotective properties)
  • Actions:
  • Aldosterone release
  • ADH release
  • ACTH release
  • Powerful vasoconstrictor (5x potency of NA)
  • Variable effects on GFR
  • Constricts efferent renal arterioles > afferent arterioles = increased GFR
  • Especially important in poor renal perfusion
  • High concentrations can contract the glomerular mesangium, leading to decreased SA for filtration, and constriction of the afferent arteriole = reduced GFR
  • Blockade of NA uptake 1 = potentiates SNS activity
  • Stimulates Na/H antiporters in the PCT = direct effect on renal tubules
  • Stimulates thirst via direct effect on hypothalamus + increased osmoreceptor activation
  • Negative feedback on renin secretion
  • Broken down in liver and kidney to inactive metabolites
  • Angiotensin II is converted to angiotensin III in many tissues by aminopeptidase; retains some activity
question3: Discuss ADH - What, stored where, secreted in response to and Actions
contents3:
• ADH is inactivated in the liver and kidney and has a half life of 18mins
  • Nonapeptide hormone synthesised in paraventricular + supraoptic nuclei, structurally similar to oxytocin
  • Stored and secreted by posterior pituitary
  • Diurnal pattern
  • Secreted in response to:
  • changes in plasma osmolality, sensed by paraventricular nuclei and supraoptic nuclei of the hypothalamus
  • Levels undetectable when osmolality < 280mOsm/kg
  • Also in response to hypovolaemia via atrial and carotid sinus / aortic arch stretch receptors
  • Also stimulated by nicotine, morphine, and barbiturates; stress, exercise
  • Effects:
  • V2 Gs-protein coupled receptors on DCT and collecting ducts = increased cAMP = aquaporin insertion
  • V1 receptors (at high conc) = arteriolar vasoconstriction and reduced renal blood flow
  • V3 receptors = release of ACTH from anterior pituitary gland
  • AVPR1A receptors = gluconeogenesis in liver
  • Does not directly affect the GFR
question4: Discuss Aldosterone - released in response to, and actions.
contents4:
• Released in response to Angiotensin II

  • Aldosterone’s effects require protein synthesis, thus taking hours
  • Increases sodium reabsorption from the gut, sweat, and saliva
  • Derived from cholesterol; acts on intracellular mineralocorticoid receptors to influence mRNA transcription
  • Half life of 30-35mins
  • No increase in urine osmolality as causes reabsorption of sodium and water
  • No significant role in acid base balance
question5: Renal vascular resistance - in order to increase GFR - what influences Afferent arteriole dilatation, and what influences Efferent arteriole constriction.
contents5:
Afferent arteriole

  • Dilatation
  • Prostaglandins
  • Kinins
  • Dopamine
  • Atrial Natriuretic peptide (++)
  • Nitric Oxide.

Efferent arteriole

  • Constriction
  • Angiotensin II
  • Sympathetic stimulation
  • Atrial Natriuretic peptide (++)

Result = ↑GFR



Afferent arteriole

  • Constriction
  • Angiotensin II
  • Sympathetic stimulation
  • Endothelin
  • Adenosine
  • Vasopressin
  • Prostaglandin blockade

Efferent arteriole

  • Dilatation
  • Angiotensin II blockade
  • Prostaglandins

Result = ↓GFR
